HMMs: generation and inference

Toy example 1

Generate data with the hidden state transitions \[ {\mathbf{A}}= \begin{pmatrix} 0.9 & 0 & 0.1 \\ 0.1 & 0.9 & 0 \\ 0 & 0.1 & 0.9 \end{pmatrix} \] and the emission probabilities \[ {\mathbf{B}}= \begin{pmatrix} 0.5 & 0 & 0 & 0.5 \\ 0 & 0 & 0.5 & 0.5 \\ 0.6 & 0.4 & 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \] A sequence of \(x\) and \(y\) of length \(n=500\).

pi = c(1/3, 1/3, 1/3)
A = rbind(c(0.9, 0, 0.1), c(0.1, 0.9, 0), c(0, 0.1, 0.9))
B = rbind(c(0.5, 0, 0, 0.5), c(0, 0, 0.5, 0.5), c(0.6, 0.4, 0, 0))

n = 500
hmm_obs = generate_discrete_HMM(n, pi, A, B)
df_true = data.frame(t = 1:n, x = hmm_obs$x)
ggplot(df_true, aes(t, x, group=1)) + 
  geom_path() + geom_point(aes(col = x)) + 
  theme_bw() + xlab("") + ggtitle("True hidden sequence")

Inference

Use Gibbs sampling to iteratively draw samples of

  • latent sequences \(x_{1:T}\) from \(p(x_{1:T} | y_{1:T}, \theta)\)
  • parameters \(\theta := (\pi, {\mathbf{A}}, {\mathbf{B}})\) from \(p(\theta | x_{1:T}, y_{1:T})\)
res = gibbs_sampling_hmm(y = hmm_obs$y, n_hidden_states = nrow(A), alpha0 = 0.1, max_iter = 1500, burnin = 500)

# relabel the latent states to obtain best match to the true B matrix
res_relabelled = match_states(res$trace_x, res$trace_A, res$trace_B, B)

Note that the labelling of the latent states is arbitrary, i.e.the model specification is invariant to relabelling the states. Here we relabel the latent states of each sample, to obtain a close match to the true values in \({\mathbf{B}}\), i.e.for each row \(i\) of the transition matrix \({\mathbf{B}}\) we find the state \(j\) such that the current sample \({\mathbf{B}}^{*}_{i, :}\) would be closest to \({\mathbf{B}}_{j, :}\) in terms of KL divergence.

Visualise samples of \(x_{1:T}\)

Each draw from the posterior is shown as a grey line. The true states are shown as coloured points.

Traceplots of the elements in \({\mathbf{A}}\)

Panel \((i, j)\) shows the traceplot for the element \({\mathbf{A}}_{ij}\). The red dotted line shows the true value.

Traceplots of the elements in \({\mathbf{B}}\)

Panel \((i, j)\) shows the traceplot for the element \({\mathbf{B}}_{ij}\). The red dotted line shows the true value.

Visualise accuracy and switch rate

For each sample of \(x_{1:T}\), I calculated two numbers:

  • pointwise accuracy having matched the latent states to be corresponding to true ones, I calculated pointwise accuracy
  • switch rate (i.e.the fraction of transitions between states)

Does not seem like a useful plot at the moment, but could become useful when comparing different approaches.
